  "text": "Found all four sandbox components:\n\n1. **Linux seccomp-BPF base policy**: `sandbox/linux/seccomp-bpf-helpers/baseline_policy.cc` (and `.h`). The class is named `BaselinePolicy` (not `BPFBasePolicy`) \u2014 it extends `bpf_dsl::Policy` and implements `EvaluateSyscall()` which delegates to `EvaluateSyscallImpl()`. This is the seccomp-BPF baseline that all Chromium Linux sandbox policies build upon (Renderer, GPU, NaCl, etc.).\n\n2. **Windows sandbox policy**: `sandbox/win/src/sandbox_policy.h` defines the abstract interfaces `TargetConfig` (shared sandbox configuration: token levels, job levels, mitigations, integrity levels, app containers) and `TargetPolicy` (per-target policy: handles, delegate data). The concrete implementation is `PolicyBase`/`ConfigBase` in `sandbox/win/src/sandbox_policy_base.h`.\n\n3. **Renderer sandbox launch configuration**: `content/browser/renderer_host/renderer_sandboxed_process_launcher_delegate.cc` (and `.h`). The class `RendererSandboxedProcessLauncherDelegate` implements `GetSandboxType()` returning `sandbox::mojom::Sandbox::kRenderer`. On Windows, `RendererSandboxedProcessLauncherDelegateWin::InitializeConfig()` configures the sandbox with handle closing, app container, dynamic code mitigations (for JIT-less renderers), and environment filtering.\n\n4. **SandboxType enum and mappings**: The `Sandbox` enum is defined in `sandbox/policy/mojom/sandbox.mojom` (as a Mojo enum with entries like `kRenderer`, `kGpu`, `kService`, etc.). The mapping logic is in `sandbox/policy/sandbox_type.cc` with functions `SandboxTypeFromCommandLine()`, `SetCommandLineFlagsForSandboxType()`, `IsUnsandboxedSandboxType()`, and `StringFromUtilitySandboxType()`/`UtilitySandboxTypeFromString()`. The header is `sandbox/policy/sandbox_type.h`.",
